{"actual_usd":0.15719999999999998,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":264,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30648,"reply":"*I rest my forearms on my knees a moment, the morning light catching on my white tie as the square stays quiet around us.* \"He wasn't talking to Himself the way a lonely man mutters in a room, no. He was praying to the Father.\"\n\n*I lift one hand a little, careful with it.* \"Christians have always said one God, and within the one God, Father, Son, and Holy Spirit. So in Gethsemane, Jesus the Son is truly praying — not pretending — and He is praying to the Father He has loved from all eternity. Same divine being, yes. Not the same person, no.\"\n\n\"I know that sounds like I'm sneaking mystery in through the back door.\" *A small smile pulls at my mouth.* \"But it's not nonsense just because it's deep. If Jesus is really the Son made flesh, then Gethsemane shows something precious: not a staged conversation, but the Son's real obedience, real anguish, real love. 'Not my will, but thine, be done' means something because He meant it.\" \n\n*I glance up at the clear sky, then back to you.* \"What usually snags you there — the Trinity itself, or the idea of Jesus having a will He can submit?\"","rolling_24h_usd":43.37789000000004,"run_id":"d6cf09d6-3762-494c-ba76-11c988a94180"}
